@page "/components/ssr-login-demo"
@*
    SSR Login Demo — this page intentionally declares NO @rendermode directive.

    It therefore renders with **static Server-Side Rendering** (.NET 8+ static SSR): there is no Blazor
    circuit or WebAssembly runtime for the page itself, so none of its own components are interactive.
    The page exists to prove that the MudKeyboard docked keyboard still works on a static-SSR page.

    Why it works without per-page interactivity:
      • <MudKeyboardHost> is registered in Components/App.razor, OUTSIDE <Routes>, with its own
        InteractiveServer render mode. It has its own circuit that stays live no matter what render
        mode the current page uses.
      • The host edits the focused <input> through JavaScript (document.activeElement) and fires native
        'input' and 'change' events, so text typed on the on-screen keyboard lands in the input's value
        and is carried by an ordinary form POST.

    Type into either field with the docked keyboard, then submit: the posted username is echoed back
    below, proving the value survived a full static-SSR form round-trip with zero per-page interactivity.
*@

<PageTitle>SSR Login Demo</PageTitle>

<MudText Typo="Typo.h4" GutterBottom="true">SSR Login Demo</MudText>
<MudText Typo="Typo.body1" Class="mb-4" Color="Color.Secondary">
    This page uses <b>static SSR</b> — it sets no render mode. The docked keyboard still slides up on
    focus and types into these fields because the keyboard host runs in its own interactive island in
    <code>App.razor</code>, outside <code>&lt;Routes&gt;</code>. Tap a field, type with the on-screen
    keyboard, then press <b>Sign in</b>.
</MudText>

<br/>

<MudText>Username : @Input.Username</MudText>
<MudText>Password : @Input.Password</MudText>

<br/>


<MudPaper Class="pa-6" Outlined="true" Style="max-width: 420px">
    <EditForm Model="Input" method="post" OnValidSubmit="HandleSubmit" FormName="ssr-login">
        <DataAnnotationsValidator />
        <MudStack Spacing="4">
            <MudKeyboardTextField @bind-Value="Input.Username"
                                  Label="Username"
                                  Variant="Variant.Outlined"
                                  DockedKeyboard="true"
                                  name="Input.Username" />

            <MudKeyboardTextField @bind-Value="Input.Password"
                                  Label="Password"
                                  Variant="Variant.Outlined"
                                  InputType="InputType.Password"
                                  DockedKeyboard="true"
                                  DockedKeyboardLayout="qwerty"
                                  name="Input.Password" />

            <MudButton ButtonType="ButtonType.Submit"
                       Variant="Variant.Filled"
                       Color="Color.Primary"
                       FullWidth="true">
                Sign in
            </MudButton>
        </MudStack>
    </EditForm>
</MudPaper>

@if (_submitted)
{
    <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Success" Variant="Variant.Filled" Class="mt-4" Style="max-width: 420px">
        Posted via static SSR — received username <b>@Input.Username</b>
        (password length @(Input.Password?.Length ?? 0)). The on-screen keyboard drove a real form POST.
    </MudAlert>
}

@code {
    // Bound from the posted form data on submit. Static-SSR form binding matches each input's
    // name attribute ("Input.Username" / "Input.Password") to this model.
#pragma warning disable BL0008 // The initializer is intentional: the form binder always supplies a non-null model on POST, and EditForm needs a non-null Model on the initial GET.
    [SupplyParameterFromForm]
    private LoginModel Input { get; set; } = new();
#pragma warning restore BL0008

    private bool _submitted;

    private void HandleSubmit() => _submitted = true;

    private sealed class LoginModel
    {
        public string? Username { get; set; }
        public string? Password { get; set; }
    }
}
